# Install venv to user home dir
# Since the workspace is a directory located on 'Windows', the ownership is always set to
# root:root when mounted to linux, which cannot be changed. Since the container will not be run as
# root as this would lead to other issues, having a normal user interract with root-owned files
# results in issues when tools need to manipulate files in the project directory, such as `uv`.
# In order to circumvent this, the venv is not created in the workspace but in the users home
# directory. Having the .venv located in the container only is perfectly fine, as Airflow can only
# be run on Unix systems, meaning the .venv is never used on Windows anyway. Furthermore, because
# the venv is installed on a Linux (ext4) filesystem, rather than a Windows (NTFS), it makes
# symlinks possible (reducing installation size a little bit), and no NTFS->ext4 translation has
# to be done (marginally improving performance).
# An alternative to using the home dir would be to run uv with sudo, but then you need to provide
# a password, environment variables would be lost, and using sudo with uv is unconventional for
# users.
# https://docs.astral.sh/uv/reference/environment/#uv_project_environment
export UV_PROJECT_ENVIRONMENT="/home/$USER/venv"
